dspace-development.title: Princeton to stop services and put 'old' Production in maintenance mode
Princeton to take final Elements backup from Production environment and upload to AWS S3 bucket

comments.body:
While testing the MSSQL backup generation utility, I have encountered a number of authorization issues:

https://princeton.service-now.com/now/workspace/agent/record/incident/6a0de2d787a6d55c9cd197183cbb358e

I am working immediately to resolve this.
The S3 `arn:aws:s3:::rdss-elements-mssql` Bucket has been created to store this on Amazon S3 (using the `pulibrary` account).
The `production` and `dev` environments have placed into maintenance mode.

The AWS policy `arn:aws:iam::080265008837:policy/rdss-elements-mssql-admin` has been created, along with the AWS user `arn:aws:iam::080265008837:user/rdss-elements-mssql-user` in order to provide access to the S3 Bucket.
The DBA from OIT is currently seeking to use the IAM `arn:aws:iam::080265008837:user/rdss-elements-mssql-user` account to access the S3 Bucket
After some troubleshooting, the DBA has authenticated, and the database export is being uploaded
The current estimate for the upload to the S3 Bucket is 4 hours.
The upload has been completed, I am going to proceed with drafting a message sharing the access to the S3 Bucket with Digital Science.
The user `arn:aws:iam::080265008837:user/rdss-elements-mssql-user` now has only read-only access to the contents of the Bucket.
The credentials and access URL have been published to LastPass using `Digital-Science-Elements\elements_mssql_amazon_S3`.
Information has been shared to the Basecamp thread using https://3.basecamp.com/3804430/buckets/26643531/todos/4720741957

figgy.title: Add migration to regenerate derivatives on filesets with too many

comments.body: Reopening until this migration is run.

Implications of this change:
- Users will no longer be able to ingest from Google Drive. We aren't aware of anyone ingesting this way any longer.
- We'll need an alternate implementation for fetching server directory locations / contents
This issue blocks migration away from webpacker because of an implementation detail in the browse everything react code
A first step might be removing the google drive feature.

Datadog keeps logs for 2 weeks. There are no logs showing an attempt to use google drive in the past 2 weeks: https://app.datadoghq.com/logs?query=service%3Afiggy%20%20%2Fbrowse%2Fproviders%2Fgoogle_drive%2Fauthorize&cols=host%2Cservice&index=&messageDisplay=inline&stream_sort=time%2Cdesc&viz=stream&from_ts=1663699135003&to_ts=1666291135003&live=true 
(vs file system: https://app.datadoghq.com/logs?query=service%3Afiggy%20%2Fbrowse%2Fproviders%2Ffast_file_system%2Fauthorize&cols=host%2Cservice&index=&messageDisplay=inline&stream_sort=time%2Cdesc&viz=stream&from_ts=1663699135003&to_ts=1666291135003&live=true). Note that this path, I believe, shows that someone selected that file source from the dropdown, not that they necessarily uploaded something with it. But it's the best I could find.

We lost the google analytics tracker in early August, but even when it was in place I don't think these browse everything routes render the layout so they don't get logged. I looked at may-june and I'm not seeing any stats on /browse.

I don't really think 2 weeks is long enough to conclude the feature's not in use.

comments.body: I see the permissions when I view the token -- will those still be viewable once it's expired?

@hackartisan I think its premature to document the permissions just yet. I want to make sure this action works and then then pare them down to the minimal required. I ticked a number that seem relevant, but I doubt they'll all be needed.

I'm not sure if the permissions will be visible once it's expired.

Here's the GitHub documentation on how to create a fine-grained access token (used to give actions permissions to create a full PR on the repo). The current token will expire 10/20/2023, which is the maximum time the token can live.

https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/keeping-your-account-and-data-secure/creating-a-personal-access-token#creating-a-fine-grained-personal-access-token

Details on the token settings when it comes time to replace it:
